# OpenOS Cursor Rules

## Package structure
- Every package in packages/ has its own tsconfig.json, package.json, and src/index.ts
- Package names use @open-os/ scope: @open-os/kernel, @open-os/sdk, @open-os/types, @open-os/cli, @open-os/mcp, @open-os/a2a
- Always import from the package name, never from relative paths across packages
- All new utilities go in the most specific package — never add shared utils to the root

## TypeScript conventions
- Strict mode always. No `any`. Use `unknown` when type is genuinely unknown.
- Prefer `interface` for public API shapes, `type` for unions and computed types
- All async functions must handle errors explicitly — no unhandled promise rejections
- Use branded types for IDs: `type AgentId = string & { __brand: 'AgentId' }`

## Agent conventions
- Every agent file exports a default AgentDefinition
- Agent IDs are kebab-case: 'web-researcher', 'code-reviewer'
- System prompts are multi-line template literals, never single-line strings
- Tool names are snake_case: 'web_search', 'fetch_page', 'read_file'
- Tool parameters are always JSON Schema objects — never plain TypeScript types

## Kernel rules
- The kernel never imports from @open-os/sdk — that dependency is one-way
- Memory stores are always created via the factory, never instantiated directly
- Every kernel operation must emit the corresponding KernelEvent
- No external HTTP calls in the kernel — adapters live in kernel/src/adapters/

## Testing rules
- Never call real LLM APIs in tests — use MockLLMAdapter
- Test files sit next to source files: scheduler.ts → scheduler.test.ts
- Every public function needs at least one happy-path and one error-path test
- Use vitest's `vi.mock` for adapter mocking, never monkeypatching

## Documentation rules
- Every exported function and class needs a JSDoc comment
- JSDoc must include: @description, @param (each), @returns, @example
- The example in JSDoc must be copy-pasteable and actually work
- Keep inline comments minimal — code should be self-documenting

## What NOT to do
- Never add framework-specific code (React, Next.js) to packages/ — that lives in apps/
- Never hardcode API keys — always read from environment variables
- Never use console.log in library code — use the kernel's logger
- Never add a dependency without checking if it can be avoided with native Node.js APIs
